---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import FaqList from '../components/FaqList.astro';
import { glocal } from '../lib/glocal';
import { faqJsonLd } from '../lib/seo';

const url = 'https://answerwithbooks.com/about/';
const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Is Answer with Books a translation site?',
    answer:
      'No. The current site is English-first, but the product direction is glocalization: global books applied to questions and constraints from Japanese and Korean readers.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Are the answers generic book summaries?',
    answer:
      'No. Book pages distill source material, while answer pages start from a practical question and use one to three books only when they improve the answer.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What role does CrowdListen play?',
    answer:
      'CrowdListen is the demand engine. It helps identify what people are asking, debating, and getting stuck on so the content roadmap starts from demand instead of guesses.',
  },
];
const jsonLd = [
  {
    '@type': 'AboutPage',
    '@id': `${url}#webpage`,
    url,
    name: 'About Answer with Books',
    description: glocal.description,
    isPartOf: { '@id': 'https://answerwithbooks.com/#website' },
    breadcrumb: { '@id': `${url}#breadcrumb` },
    mainEntity: { '@id': 'https://answerwithbooks.com/#person' },
  },
  {
    '@type': 'Person',
    '@id': 'https://answerwithbooks.com/#person',
    name: 'Terry Chen',
    url: 'https://terrylinhaochen.github.io',
  },
  {
    '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
    '@id': `${url}#breadcrumb`,
    itemListElement: [
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Answer with Books', item: 'https://answerwithbooks.com/' },
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'About', item: url },
    ],
  },
  {
    ...faqJsonLd(url, faqs),
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="About"
  description={glocal.description}
  path="/about/"
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-5 pt-16 pb-16">
    <h1 class="font-serif text-4xl font-semibold tracking-tight">About</h1>

    <div class="prose-awb mt-8">
      <h2>What this is</h2>
      <p>
        Answer with Books is a public version of something I'd been keeping privately: a shelf of
        books that don't just gather dust after being read, but stay <em>on call</em>.
      </p>
      <p>
        The glocal version is the product direction: global books, local questions, with Japanese
        and Korean readers first. The site stays grounded in English-language source books where
        that is the strongest material, but the demand engine, examples, and answer framing are
        meant to reflect what people in Japan and Korea are actually trying to figure out.
      </p>
      <p>
        The premise is simple. A good book usually contains three to six ideas worth keeping —
        mental models, frameworks, ways of seeing. The rest is scaffolding. So every book I read
        gets a <a href="/books/">distilled page</a>: the load-bearing ideas, the frameworks worth
        actually using, when to reach for the book, and what happened when I applied it.
      </p>
      <p>
        Then the books get put to work. The <a href="/answers/">answers</a> take real, practical
        questions — <em>How to validate an idea without fooling yourself, how to keep a smart team
        from making a dumb decision, how to tell whether to pivot or keep going</em> — and answer
        them by combining one to three books with local demand signals and first-hand experience.
        Every answer cites its sources and links back to the shelf, so you can go as deep as the
        question deserves.
      </p>
      <p>
        No summaries of summaries. No books I haven't read. The test for everything published here:
        would a smart, busy reader bookmark this page and come back to it before a real decision?
      </p>

      <h2>Who I am</h2>
      <p>
        I'm <strong>Terry Chen</strong> — a builder studying at Northwestern University, currently
        working on <strong>CrowdListen</strong>, a product for understanding what audiences and
        crowds actually think. A lot of the books on this shelf earned their place by being useful
        in that work: <a href="/books/the-mom-test/">The Mom Test</a> for talking to users,
        <a href="/books/the-wisdom-of-crowds/">The Wisdom of Crowds</a> for designing aggregation,
        <a href="/books/seeing-like-a-state/">Seeing Like a State</a> for staying honest about what
        dashboards delete.
      </p>

      <h2>Why Japan and Korea</h2>
      <p>
        A lot of high-quality advice assumes a Silicon Valley or broad American default. That can be
        useful, but it often misses how school pressure, workplace hierarchy, customer behavior,
        language, family expectations, and market structure change the problem. Answer with Books is
        meant to adapt the best book ideas to those local constraints instead of copying the same
        generic answer everywhere.
      </p>
      <p>
        More about me and my other writing lives at
        <a href="https://terrylinhaochen.github.io">terrylinhaochen.github.io</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>What the account is for</h2>
      <p>
        You can read everything here without one. A free <a href="/signup/">account</a> lets you
        save books and localized answers for later; more account features are on the way.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
  <FaqList items={faqs} eyebrow="About Q&A" title="How to read this project" />
</Base>
